It is reasonable to assume the data is sampled from a somewhat normal distribution. The QQ plot reveals that the quantiles of the sample are aligning with the theoretical quantiles of $\mathcal{N}(0, 1)$. The histogram additionally supports that.

a.2) Compute a point estimate for µ. Derive, assuming normality (irrespective of your conclusion about normality od the data), a bounded 90% confidence interval for µ.

As a point estimate for $\mu$, the sample mean $\bar{X} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_i X_i$ is used.

In [6]:
alpha = 0.1
n = length(births)
mu_estimate = mean(births)
sigma_estimate = sd(births)
In [7]:
mu_estimate
2913.29255319149

Since $\sigma$ is unknown, we have to use $s$ to create a confidence interval for our estimate and therefore the t-test. The CI is obtained via

$$ \bar{X} \pm t_{\alpha / 2} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}=\left[\bar{X}-t_{\alpha / 2} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}, \bar{X}+t_{\alpha / 2} \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}\right] $$
In [8]:
t_alpha = qt(1-(alpha/2),df=n-1)
CI = c(mu_estimate - (t_alpha) * (sigma_estimate / sqrt(n)),
       mu_estimate + (t_alpha) * (sigma_estimate / sqrt(n)))
CI
  1. 2829.20154724168
  2. 2997.3835591413

$\bar{X} = 2913$ is concluded to be an appropiate estimate for the population mean since $\bar{X} \in [ 2830 , 3000]$ (90 % CI). Alternatively, we chan check that via the t-test :

In [9]:
t.test(births,mu=2913, conf.level = 0.9)

$H_0$ is rejected, $p < 0.05$. If we vary $\alpha$, the CIs will change according to the previously used formula for the CI. While the upper bound wont change, the lower bound of the CI will.

c.) In the R-output of the test from b), also a confidence interval is given, but why is it different from the confidence interval found in a) and why is it one-sided?

This is expected if the hypothesis is one-tailed ( >, <), the CI is also one-sided, effectively yielding an upper or lower bound , i.e $\left(-\infty, \bar{X}+t_{\alpha, n-1} \frac{S}{\sqrt{n}}\right)$ or $\left(\bar{X}-t_{\alpha, n-1} \frac{S}{\sqrt{n}},+\infty\right)$.

In this specific case we are looking for upper confidence bounds, which gives us the ability to check for membership of 2800 in order to reject/accept.

Exc. 2 - Power function of the t-test¶

We study the power function of the two-sample t-test. \ For n=m=30, mu=180, nu=175 and sd=5, generate 1000 samples x=rnorm(n,mu,sd) and y=rnorm(m,nu,sd), and record the 1000 p-values for testing H0: mu=nu. \ You can evaluate the power (at point nu=175) of this t-test as fraction of p-values that are smaller than 0.05.

Note that $H_0 : \mu = \nu \implies H_0 : \mu - \nu = 0 $, which seems to be the calculation baseline for the t object implemented in R. The power of the test is $$ \textbf{power} = P(\textit{Reject} \ H_0| \neg H_0 ) $$

In [14]:
#sample size
n=m=30
#total samples
N = 1000
#density props
x_mean = 180
y_mean= 175
std = 5
In [15]:
p_vals = numeric(N)
for(i in 1:N){p_vals[i]=t.test(x=rnorm(m, x_mean, std),
                                      y=rnorm(n, y_mean, std))$p.value}
In [16]:
# Estimated density of MC-pseudo p-values
hist(p_vals)
In [17]:
power = length(p_vals[p_vals<0.05])/length(p_vals)
power
0.975

Given power $P\in [0,1]$, $P=0.97$ looks good. It represents the power of the test at $\nu = 175$ i.e.

$$ P(\textit{Reject} \ H_0| \neg H_0 ) \approx 97 \% \ \ \text{for} \ \nu = 175 $$

which is the ratio of rejecting vs accpeting.

a.) Set n=m=30, mu=180 and sd=5. Calculate now the power of the t-test for every value of nu in the grid seq(175,185,by=0.25). Plot the power as a function of nu.

In [18]:
#linear space
linspace = seq(175,185,by=0.25)
pwr = function(y_mean, x_mean=180, m=30, n=30, std=5, N=1000){
p_vals = numeric(N);
for(i in 1:N){p_vals[i]=t.test(x=rnorm(m, x_mean, std),
                                      y=rnorm(n, y_mean, std))$p.value}
power = length(p_vals[p_vals<0.05])/length(p_vals);
return(power)
}
In [19]:
powers = sapply(linspace, pwr)
plot(x=linspace, y=powers)

We should only reject $H_0$ if $\neg H_0$. Obviously $\neg H_0 \ \forall \ \nu \neq 180 \implies P(\textit{Reject} \ H_0| \neg H_0 ) = 0 \ \ \text{for} \ \nu = 180 $ which is similar to comparing the locations of the underlying densities.

Both the sample size and the std of the samples have an impact on the power of the tests. \ Large sample sizes will make the test near to optimal, indicated by approaching a step function for $p\in \{0,1\}$. \ Increasing the standard deviation makes any kind of sensible test and its power less stable and ultimately noisy.

Bootstrap test¶

b) By using a bootstrap test with the test statistic T = median(X1, . . . , X200), test whether the data telephone.txt stems from the exponential distribution Exp(λ) with some λ from [0.01, 0.1].

$$ H_0 \gets X \sim \text{exp}(\lambda) $$

with $T(X)$ as the median, i.e $T^{*}_b = T(X^{*}_b)$.

In [26]:
# Median of original data
t_init = median(survey)
t_init
28.905
In [27]:
linspace= seq(0.01, 0.1,by=0.005)
p_vals = c()
for(lambda in linspace){ 
    B = 1000
    T_star = numeric(B)
    for(b in 1:B){
        # Create bootstrap sample of same size as original sample drawn from exp(lambda)
        X_star=rexp(length(survey), lambda)
        # Compute test statistic for b-th bootstrap sample
        T_star[b]=median(X_star)
    }
    pl = sum(T_star<t_init)/B;
    pr = sum(T_star>t_init)/B;
    p = 2*min(pl, pr);
    p_vals = c(p_vals,p)
}
options(repr.plot.width=6, repr.plot.height=4)
plot(x=linspace, y=p_vals,type="b")

Evaluating $\lambda \in [0.01,0.1]$ reveals $\lambda=0.025$ is potentially reasonable, given that $t$ is less than one standard deviation away from the mean of the median under $\text{exp}(0.025)$. \ While the p-value is insignificant for most other values of $\lambda$, testing $t$ under $\text{exp}(0.025)$ yields $p=0.69$. Notably, $\text{exp}(0.020)$ yields $p=0.096$ which can also not be rejected !!

Using CLT to evaluate $\lambda \in \{0.025, 0.02\}$.¶

For the exponential distribution with $\mu=\frac{1}{\lambda}$ and $\sigma^2 =\frac{1}{\lambda^2}$ we can use the CLT to standardize $\bar{X}$ into $\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}}=\frac{\bar{X}-1 / \lambda}{\frac{1}{\lambda} / \sqrt{n}}$, which we can simplify to $\sqrt{n}(\lambda \bar{X}-1)$, for which it is non-trivial to show that $\sqrt{n}(\lambda \bar{X}-1) \sim N(0,1)$ . For every lambda we can generate a bunch of samples with the same size as the initial sample and get the distribution of $\sqrt{n}(\lambda \bar{X}-1)$. We can then compare our initial value with the two distributions to obtain two p-values.

In [32]:
B = 1000
t_init_1 = sqrt(length(survey))*(0.025*mean(survey) - 1)
t_init_2 = sqrt(length(survey))*(0.020*mean(survey) - 1)
lambda1 = numeric(B)
lambda2 = numeric(B)
p_vals_1 = c()
p_vals_2 = c()
for(b in 1:B){
    X_star1=rexp(length(survey), 0.025)
    X_star2=rexp(length(survey), 0.020)
    # Compute normalized mean
    lambda1[b]=sqrt(length(survey))*(0.025*mean(X_star1) - 1)
    lambda2[b]=sqrt(length(survey))*(0.020*mean(X_star2) - 1)
}
    pl = sum(lambda1<t_init_1)/B;
    pr = sum(lambda1>t_init_1)/B;
    p = 2*min(pl, pr);
    p_vals_1 = c(p_vals_1,p)
    pl = sum(lambda2<t_init_2)/B;
    pr = sum(lambda2>t_init_2)/B;
    p = 2*min(pl, pr);
    p_vals_2 = c(p_vals_2,p)
par(mfrow=c(1,2));options(repr.plot.width=10, repr.plot.height=3)
hist(lambda1,prob=TRUE);hist(lambda2,prob=TRUE)
In [33]:
c(p_vals_2,#.020
  p_vals_1)#.025
  1. 0.19
  2. 0.062

Given $p_{\lambda=0.02} > p_{\lambda=0.025}$, we essentially end up at the same conclusion as using a bootstrap test with mean as test statistic.

e.1)Using an appropriate test, test the null hypothesis that the median bill is bigger or equal to 40 euro against the alternative that the median bill is smaller than 40 euro.

In [34]:
median(survey)
28.905

$H_0 : m \geq 40$

By definition of the median, 50% of the values lie above/below. If $m \geq 40$ then we expect that at least $\frac{n}{2}$ of the values are smaller than 40.

$$ m=40 \implies P(X < 40) = P(X > 40) \\ m>40 \implies P(X < 40) > P(X > 40) \\ m<40 \implies P(X < 40) < P(X > 40) \\ $$

For $m \geq 40$, $P(X < 40) \geq 0.5$ must hold.

In [35]:
length(survey[survey < 40])/length(survey)
0.567708333333333
In [36]:
binom.test(length(survey[survey < 40]), length(survey), p = 0.5, alternative="less")

	Exact binomial test

data:  length(survey[survey < 40]) and length(survey)
number of successes = 109, number of trials = 192, p-value = 0.9745
alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is less than 0.5
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.0000000 0.6280198
sample estimates:
probability of success 
             0.5677083

We cannot reject $H_0$. The true probability is likeli to be above 50%, which is what we were asking for!

a.) Test whether the distributions of the chicken weights for meatmeal and sunflower groups are different by performing three tests: the two samples t-test (argue whether the data are paired or not), the Mann-Whitney test and the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test. Comment on your findings.

a.1) Two sample t-test¶

The data does not come in the form of matched pairs, but the experiments are rather statistically independent. Thats why we cannot perform the paired t test. If we would have two outcomes per unit (chicken) we could do the paired test. Using the two sample t-test, we find that $H_0 : \mu_1 = \mu_2$ needs to be rejected for $\alpha=0.05$.

In [7]:

 -102.572435   -1.442716

a.2) Mann-Whitney Test¶

Now using a rank-based method, namely the Mann-Whitney test, we are able to evaluate $H_0 : f_1 = f_2$, specifically the location shift of the underlying densities $f_1, f_2$ is assumed to be zero in $H_0$. For $\alpha=0.05$, we cannot reject $H_0$ according to the Mann-Whitney test, which is contrary to the first test, although the two sample t-test is only slight off with $p=0.044$.

In [8]:
wilcox.test(meatmeal, sunflower)

alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
a.3) Kolmogorov Smirnov Test¶

Using the eCDFs of the samples, we can use the KS-test to again evaluate $H_0 : f_1 = f_2$ . The two-sample K–S test is much more useful than the methods used before, not only because it is mostly assumptionless, but because it is sensitive to differences in both location and shape of the underlying distributions (unlike the previous tests). The KS-test accepts $H_0$ with $\alpha=0.05$

In [9]:
ks.test(meatmeal, sunflower)

data:  meatmeal and sunflower
D = 0.47727, p-value = 0.1085
alternative hypothesis: two-sided

model = lm(weight~feed,data=chickwts)

For the factor test we evaluate $H_0 : \mu_1 = \mu_2 = ... \mu_l$ , given the $l$ factors (feed types), i.e there is no difference in weihgt among feed types. Like in the previous tests, the larger the test statistic (in this case the F-value) the more likely $H_0$ is rejected. The observed p-value of $H_0$ is very small and we therefore need to reject $H_0$, indicating significant difference in weight among the factors.

From the summary table of the linear model we can see that casein serves as the baseline factor.

$$ (\mu_0, \mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3, \mu_4, \mu_5) \gets (323.6, 160.2, 218.8, 276.9, 246.4, 328.9) $$

where $\mu_0$ is the casein mean. Casein and sunflower are both having significant larger estimated locations than the other feed types, but the SE of sunflower is a little bit smaller. If we look at the boxplots, we see that sunflower is generally more compact around its median, while casein has a higher variance, but doesnt has extreme outliers like sunflower, which may cause high SE of OLS estimates.

d.) Does the Kruskal-Wallis test arrive at the same conclusion about the effect of feed supplement as the test in b)? Explain possible differences between conclusions of the Kruskal-Wallis and ANOVA tests

In [21]:
kruskal.test(chickwts$weight,chickwts$feed)

	Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test

data:  chickwts$weight and chickwts$feed
Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 37.343, df = 5, p-value = 5.113e-07

While ANOVA/t-tests basically compares means, Kruskal-Wallis/Mann-Whitney is comparing the mean ranks, which is more general and works not only for samples that stem from normal densities. For large factor effects like the ones shown in this dataset, both tests will very likeli come to the same conclusion, although they are, as previously described, not necessarily measuring the same underyling population metrics.
